\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edgar_Adrian,_1st_Baron_Adrian\" title=\"Edgar Adrian, 1st Baron Adrian\">Edgar Adrian, 1st Baron Adrian<\/a>, in 1932 for their work on the functions of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Neuron\" title=\"Neuron\">neurons<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charles_Scott_Sherrington#cite_note-9\"><span>[<\/span>9<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charles_Scott_Sherrington#cite_note-10\"><span>[<\/span>10<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Prior to the work of Sherrington and Adrian, it was widely accepted that <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Reflex\" title=\"Reflex\">reflexes<\/a> occurred as isolated activity within a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Reflex_arc\" title=\"Reflex arc\">reflex arc<\/a>. Sherrington received the prize for showing that reflexes require integrated activation and demonstrated reciprocal innervation of muscles (<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sherrington%27s_law_of_reciprocal_innervation\" title=\"Sherrington's law of reciprocal innervation\">Sherrington's law<\/a>).<sup id=\"cite_ref-NobelPrize.org_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charles_Scott_Sherrington#cite_note-NobelPrize.org-11\"><span>[<\/span>11<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charles_Scott_Sherrington#cite_note-12\"><span>[<\/span>12<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Charles Scott Sherrington","place_of_birth":"Islington ,  London ,  England","place_of_death":"Eastbourne ,  Sussex ,  England","text":"Charles Scott Sherrington , Physiology or Medicine, 1932","year":1932.0}